  "text": "This section describes how to extend a standard New Keynesian model with the introduction of banking elements and endogenous capital accumulation. Most of the banking sector has been adapted from the model described by [CITATION_1] , henceforth referred to as GM (2007) . In particular, there is a loan production technology, a deposit-in-advance constraint, and nominal interest rates for bonds, loans and interbank lending. One of the differences with respect to GM (2007) is the presence of variable capital and adjustment costs on capital changes. Thus, we introduce an investment function, used by Woodford (2003, chapter 5) , that incorporates adjustment costs of changes in the stock of capital:",
